<Base title="Layer Your Verification — Augmented Engineering">
  <PatternPage number="2" title="Layer Your Verification" subtitle="V&V became cheap enough to use routinely. Each layer catches what the others miss.">

    <p>The pattern: <strong>agent generates &rarr; agent reviews &rarr; agent validates &rarr; engineer decides.</strong> Independent V&V has existed since the 1970s — mandatory in avionics, medical devices, nuclear systems. In most other engineering, it was too expensive.</p>

    <p>AI agents change the economics. Three, four, five verification passes now cost minutes. This doesn't change the principle. It changes who gets to use it.</p>

    <div class="illustration-wrap">
      <IllustrationLayers />
    </div>

    <div class="monday-box">
      <h3>Try This Monday</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>After your AI generates output, don't review it yourself first — have a second AI pass review it with different instructions.</li>
        <li>After that review, ask: "what might both passes have missed?" Run a third pass focused on that question.</li>
        <li>Classify items by risk. Spend thorough verification on the high-consequence items. Spot-check the rest.</li>
        <li>The marginal cost of each additional layer is minutes. Err on the side of one more layer.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Where to Apply It</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Phase</th><th>What Agents Verify</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Requirements</td><td>Consistency, testability, conflict detection</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Architecture</td><td>Interface checks, performance estimation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Detailed Design</td><td>Equation reproduction, safety analysis</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Testing</td><td>Coverage gaps, test case generation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Documentation</td><td>Claim-evidence tracing, confidence calibration</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Where This Comes From</h2>

    <p>A mixed-signal PCB design for a confocal optical instrument. 725 checklist items across 14 disciplines, verified in layers.</p>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>Stopping after one pass would have left 8 of 10 defects undiscovered.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Found</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>P0 verification</td><td>Laser boot hazard, LDO undersized</td></tr>
        <tr><td>V&V audit (auditing the auditors)</td><td>Motor driver logic pin missing entirely</td></tr>
        <tr><td>P1 spot-check</td><td>ADC timing, PWM safety regression, thermal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Full P1</td><td>Reference impedance, DAC init, firmware safety</td></tr>
        <tr><td>+ local datasheets</td><td>Voltage drop, 10x resistance error</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>The most concerning: a PWM resolution limit caused a safety voltage cap to silently map to 4.1V instead of 2.0V. A safety regression hidden inside an apparent safety fix — found only by layer 3.</p>

    <div class="caveat-box">
      <h3>Honest Limitations</h3>
      <p>This is one design review of one instrument. "8 of 10 missed by single-pass" is specific to this design — it demonstrates the principle but doesn't quantify a general rate. Open question: when does the nth layer stop finding defects?</p>
    </div>

  </PatternPage>
</Base>

